ing.  As a result, even the folks at Verant probably have never stopped to think how there can be ways to give different classes some perks to being a caster since there is virtually no BENEFIT to being a caster at the low levels for wizards and other classes.  <br>
<br>
So, for the types of spells, we have:<br>
DD spells<br>
stun spells<br>
stun spells with damage<br>
root spells<br>
snare spells<br>
DD spells with stun<br>
DD spells with knock-back<br>
Invis<br>
Invis to Undead<br>
Levitate<br>
Vision alteration spells(lame gaze spells, bind sight which was nerfed)<br>
<br>
The list goes on, but if you look at spell names, there are clearly a lot of ways that these DIFFERENT spells would come into play to make things interesting.<br>
<br>
<br>
The original root spell, which makes the target get STUCK to the ground would be very useful since the mob wouldn't be able to turn, and couldn't attack you if you were behind it(except some mobs that don't have a front or back(goos for example)<br>
<br>
Enstill might be more like a paralyze, it just doesn't move.  It would be similar to a mez for effect.<br>
<br>
Bonds of Force wouldn't have to be an AE spell, but could be more like a normal snare is currently<br>
<br>
Snare would limit the mob from moving too far from where the spell took hold.  It's a SNARE, it catches the mob by the foot, and hauls it into the air, or to the ground where it might not have much room, but it can't get away.<br>
<br>
Atol's Spectral Shackles on the other hand, could be a reduce attack, reduce defense, and reduce movement rate(the mob is shackled, wrists and feet.<br>
<br>
The other root and snare spells out there, the DD spells that have cool sounding names but don't really have an effect, all of these things could be made to be DIFFERENT, and so would define the classes a bit more.  And isn't that really what the problem has been, a lack of class identity when we are playing?<br>
<br>
Stuns as well, is there a reason why Verant thinks of stuns as being ONLY caused by a blow to the head?<br>
<br>
If you do 25 percent or more of a mob's current hit points in one shot, don't you figure the mob's nervous system would be affected, and possibly stop working for a moment?  For different classes, obviously, they would have some of these type of abilities, but wizards, we get the big damage spells(or theoretically).  If you pound a mob hard enough and fast enough, it SHOULD stun.  <br>
<br>
So, wizard balance would be that we cast a high damage spell, and it stuns the mob.<br>
<br>
Enchanters can affect the mind, and make the mob feel the pain so that it gets stunned.<br>
<br>
Necromancers use spells to cause pain and &quot;shock&quot; the mobs.<br>
<br>
Electrical damage also has a tendancy of causing things to be unable to move even.  Don't believe me, stick a fork in an electrical outlet(no, don't really do this, but you get the idea).<br>
<br>
So, all classes should be able to stun, but not in the same way, and the spells shouldn't just be a duplication of the effect that other classes get.  <br>
<br>
IF Verant were to rework the spells so they took this sort of thing into account, the classes, even at lower levels might be balanced a bit better.  Shock of frost even might give a very small attack debuff for example since the COLD side of it might make the muscles of certain mobs to cramp for a few seconds at least.  This doesn't increase damage output, but DOES help in a small way at the very low levels.<br>
<br>
<br>
What do you think?<br>
